Pulsar

——Observations, Standard Model Difficulties, and a Natural Explanation in the Topological Defect Weaving Framework

Abstract

We take as our starting point a mechanism rejected by the standard model — cold fusion. In our framework, cold fusion is interpreted as defect‑complementary weaving (Path I) on nuclide surfaces: when two defects are geometrically complementary, spontaneous engagement releases stress energy, independent of energy barriers. The single‑event probability is extremely low and depends strongly on nuclide species and environmental conditions. Constrained by observed thermal fluxes, the effective probability of Path I is ∼10⁻²⁹ in the solar core and ∼10⁻³² for Jupiter (whole‑body weighted). When particle numbers reach astrophysical scales (>10⁵⁷), these low probabilities are locked by the law of large numbers into observable macroscopic event rates. Inside neutron stars, ultra‑high density, solid‑state anisotropic stress fields, and continuous compression yield effective reaction rates far exceeding solar‑core conditions. Energy released by Path I drives the local centre of the star across the threshold for Path II (forced chain reconnection); Path II is then triggered at the high‑energy core region with a small fraction of participating nuclides, releasing a shockwave and generating pulses. After each pulse, the star returns to Path I, re‑accumulates stress, and repeats the cycle. This single mechanism consistently explains pulsar periods, pulse widths, profiles, glitches, magnetars, the death line, and other phenomena, requiring no additional assumptions such as magnetic inclination, superfluidity, vortex pinning, or extreme magnetic fields. Theoretically, Path III (topological dissolution) may exist when the topological charges of two nuclides sum to zero, leading to complete annihilation into pure energy.

Keywords: pulsar; compact topological star; defect‑complementary weaving; forced chain reconnection; total compressive binding energy; shockwave; cold fusion

Preliminary Note

Throughout this paper, the topological knots inside the pulsar are collectively referred to as “nuclides” (Nuclide). This term denotes all types of nuclear configurations and is not restricted to any particular element or isotope. The weaving complexity of different nuclides determines their physical behaviour, but the pulsar emission mechanism itself does not depend on a specific nuclide species.

Introduction: A Rejected Mechanism, Reborn on Astrophysical Scales

Cold fusion — the spontaneous combination of nuclides at low temperatures releasing energy — was rejected by the standard model. The reason is straightforward: in the laboratory, the reaction probability is too low, the signal lies far below detection thresholds, and standard physics therefore concluded that “this path is closed”.

But on astrophysical scales, the situation is completely different. A compact star contains about 10⁵⁷ nuclides. Even if the single‑collision engagement probability is extremely low, the absolute number of events can still reach a macroscopically observable level. The law of large numbers locks the microscopic probabilities into definite macroscopic statistical event rates. In the solar core, the macroscopic heat release from Path I matches the observed luminosity; in Jupiter’s interior, Path I explains the observed anomalous heat flux. Path I was never falsified — it merely becomes observable only on astrophysical scales.

From this, we set out to re‑interpret all observed pulsar phenomena.

A pulsar is a solid, compact remnant. Inside, gravitational compression continues, and nuclides release tiny amounts of heat through defect‑complementary weaving (Path I), accumulating stress in the topological network. Because the total number of particles is enormous, even an extremely small fraction of participating nuclides still yields an absolute number large enough to produce observable macroscopic effects, driving the local centre of the star across the threshold for triggering Path II.

When the accumulated stress in the central region reaches the total compressive binding energy (E_抗压), Path II is triggered — the connecting edges are sheared in bulk, and a chain reconnection releases a shockwave on millisecond timescales. The shockwave propagates through the solid star to the entire surface, producing a “squash‑head” spallation ejection. The observer can receive signals only from a very narrow line‑of‑sight direction.

After the pulse, the star returns to Path I, re‑accumulates stress, and waits for the next statistical crossing of the threshold. The cycle repeats.

1. Observed Facts of Pulsars

Since the discovery of the first pulsar by Hewish et al. in 1967, the accumulated basic parameters are as follows:

Parameter	Typical value / range
Pulse period P	1.4 ms – 8.5 s
Period derivative Ṗ	10⁻²¹ – 10⁻¹¹ s/s
Pulse width W	1 – 50 ms (3%–4% of period)
Radio luminosity	10²⁴ – 10³¹ erg/s
Characteristic age τ = P/(2Ṗ)	10³ – 10⁷ yr
Surface magnetic field (inferred)	10⁸ – 10¹³ G
Pulse profiles are diverse (single, double, multiple peaks). Some pulsars exhibit nulling (sudden disappearance and reappearance of pulses), subpulse drifting, and glitches (ΔP/P ∼ 10⁻⁹–10⁻⁶). Magnetars (soft gamma repeaters and anomalous X‑ray pulsars) have luminosities far exceeding their spin‑down energy loss rates, radiating in X‑ray and gamma‑ray bands.

2. The Standard Model: Framework and Systemic Difficulties

2.1 Basic Assumptions of the Lighthouse Model

The standard interpretation of pulsars rests on the following assumptions:

Pulsars are rapidly rotating, strongly magnetized neutron stars;
Radiation comes from charged particles accelerated along open magnetic field lines in the magnetosphere;
The magnetic axis is misaligned with the rotation axis (magnetic inclination);
The radiation beam is conical and sweeps across the sky as the star rotates;
A pulse is seen when the line of sight intercepts the beam.
This model successfully explains the periodicity (rotation period) and stability (rigid rotation) of pulsars. However, the following difficulties remain unresolved.

2.2 Difficulty I: Magnetic Inclination is an Ad‑Hoc Assumption, Not a Necessary Consequence

The lighthouse model requires a misalignment between the magnetic and rotation axes. This condition is not derived from the physics – it is a geometrical assumption added after the fact.

To explain the low duty cycle (3%–4%), one needs fine‑tuned combinations of inclination angle and emission height. This is essentially parameter tuning. Some pulsars require inclination angles smaller than 20° to account for wide beams.

More fundamentally: why must the magnetic axis be misaligned? Long‑term evolutionary models predict that the inclination angle should decay toward zero over time, which creates tension with the observed population of pulsars.

2.3 Difficulty II: Magnetic Field Strength is an Inferred Quantity, Leading to Circular Reasoning

In the standard model, the spin‑down is attributed to magnetic dipole radiation carrying away rotational kinetic energy. The dipole radiation power depends on the surface magnetic field strength B, but B is not an independently measured quantity; it is inferred from:

B ∝ √(PṖ)

One observes P and Ṗ → calculates B → then uses B to “explain” Ṗ. This is circular reasoning: the same data are used both to establish the existence of a magnetic field and to explain the data with that field.

The correlation between P and Ṗ exists, but a correlation does not prove that magnetic dipole radiation is the causal mechanism.

2.4 Difficulty III: Glitches Require Two Extra Assumptions (Superfluidity and Vortex Pinning)

Sudden increases in spin frequency (glitches) are explained in the standard model as a rapid exchange of angular momentum with a superfluid interior: superfluid vortices are pinned to the crustal lattice, do not follow the spin‑down, and then suddenly release accumulated angular momentum.

This explanation introduces at least two unverified assumptions:

Existence of superfluid neutrons inside the neutron star (whether superfluidity exists at supra‑nuclear densities is not confirmed);
The vortex‑pinning mechanism (the pinning force and its spatial distribution are not known).
As researchers admit, “pulsar glitch theory must be connected to observations through superfluid dynamics, using the moment of inertia and the post‑glitch recovery timescale” – i.e., fitting observations with unknown parameters.

2.5 Difficulty IV: The Death Line has been Observationally Refuted

The standard model predicts a “death line” in the P–Ṗ diagram below which the magnetospheric voltage cannot sustain coherent radio emission and pulsations should cease entirely.

This theoretical boundary has been repeatedly contradicted by observations. PSR J2129+4119 (period 1.69 s, characteristic age 340 Myr) lies far below the conventional death line, yet exhibits persistent multi‑mode emission including nulling, weak pulses, regular radiation, and occasional bright pulses. Researchers have concluded that “the death line is not a physical boundary, but merely an as‑yet‑ununderstood region of parameter space”.

2.6 Difficulty V: Magnetars Require an Extra Assumption of Ultra‑Strong Magnetic Fields

The high‑energy luminosity of magnetars far exceeds their spin‑down power. The standard model invokes “ultra‑strong magnetic fields” (>10¹⁴ G) to explain this, but how the magnetic field energy is converted into such violent bursts lacks a self‑consistent mechanism.

The 2004 giant flare of SGR 1806‑20 released about 1.3×10⁴⁰ W – equivalent to the total energy output of the Sun over 150,000 years. The standard model has no convincing explanation for how magnetic energy can be converted so quickly and repeatedly into radiation.

2.7 Difficulty VI: The Equation of State (EOS) is Highly Uncertain

All predictions of the standard model – mass‑radius relation, maximum mass, possible quark cores – depend on the nuclear equation of state. In the supra‑nuclear density regime (>2 times nuclear density), the EOS uncertainty is well known.

When determining the radius of a 1.4 M⊙ neutron star, “the dependence on the EOS model introduces large systematic uncertainties”. This means that the standard model predicts hypothetical objects with an uncertain foundation.

3. The Topological Defect Weaving Framework

3.1 From Cold Fusion to Path I: Probability Statistics on Astrophysical Scales

The standard model’s rejection of cold fusion is justified on laboratory scales: single‑collision engagement probabilities are extremely low, and in a laboratory with limited particle numbers and observation time, the signal is buried in background.

But on astrophysical scales, the situation is entirely different. A compact star contains ∼10⁵⁷ nuclides. The event rate of Path I is determined by the total number of nuclides, the collision frequency, and the single‑event engagement probability. Even if the probability is extremely low and only an extremely small fraction of nuclides satisfy the conditions within a statistical time window, their absolute number can still reach a macroscopically observable level.

Using observed thermal fluxes as constraints, we infer the effective probability of Path I:

Solar core: Path I effective probability ∼10⁻²⁹

Calculation basis: Solar luminosity L⊙ = 3.828×10²⁶ W. Assume each Path I engagement releases ∼10⁻¹² J (MeV scale). Required total event rate Ṅ = 3.828×10²⁶ / 10⁻¹² ≈ 3.8×10³⁸ s⁻¹. Solar core contains ∼10⁵⁷ particles. Per‑particle per‑second effective probability ≈ 3.8×10³⁸ / 10⁵⁷ ≈ 3.8×10⁻¹⁹ s⁻¹. Collision frequency in the solar core is about 10⁶–10¹¹ s⁻¹, giving a single‑collision matching probability between 3.8×10⁻²⁵ and 3.8×10⁻³⁰; we adopt the order‑of‑magnitude value 10⁻²⁹. The solar core is dominated by hydrogen nuclei (protons), comprising about 70% of the mass.

Jupiter (whole‑body weighted): Path I effective probability ∼10⁻³²

Calculation basis: Jupiter’s anomalous heat flux is about 7.5×10¹⁷ W. Jupiter’s total particle number is ∼10⁵⁴. Required total event rate Ṅ = 7.5×10¹⁷ / 10⁻¹² ≈ 7.5×10²⁹ s⁻¹. Per‑particle per‑second effective probability ≈ 7.5×10²⁹ / 10⁵⁴ ≈ 7.5×10⁻²⁵ s⁻¹. Collision frequency inside Jupiter is ∼10³–10⁶ s⁻¹, giving a single‑collision matching probability between 7.5×10⁻²⁸ and 7.5×10⁻³¹; we adopt the order‑of‑magnitude value 10⁻³² as the whole‑body weighted average. Jupiter is composed mainly of hydrogen with a significant fraction of helium and light nuclides; the diversity of nuclide species systematically lowers the matching probability compared with the pure‑hydrogen environment of the solar core.

The difference of about three orders of magnitude reflects the systematic influence of nuclide species and environmental conditions (temperature, density, pressure gradient) on the defect‑matching probability. This is not a divergence of a constant, but a natural manifestation of environmental dependence.

Key inference: Path I was never falsified – it becomes observable only on astrophysical scales.

3.2 Definition of the Compact Topological Star

A pulsar is the remnant of a supernova explosion. After the explosion, the residual core, under gravitational compression, forms a solid compact star – an extremely thick solid crust on the outside and an ultra‑compressed topological network inside. We define this object as a compact topological star, without presupposing a “neutronised” composition.

Its essential features are:

Solid interface: The surface is a rigid, saturation‑connected topological network that can accumulate, reflect, and transmit stress;
Rich internal nuclides: The remnant still contains a large number of nuclides of various types, and Path I continues to operate;
Saturation‑rigid support: The network nodes reach maximum coordination number and resist further compression (the topological analogue of the standard model’s “neutron degeneracy pressure”);
Energy accumulation condition: Because the medium is solid, there is no fluid expansion cooling; the energy released by Path I cannot be regulated by negative feedback and therefore accumulates inside.
3.3 Three Fundamental Pathways

Path I (defect‑complementary weaving): When the defects of two topological knots are geometrically complementary, they spontaneously engage, reconnecting edges and releasing stress energy. The only barrier is geometric matching. In a fluid medium, Path I has a natural negative‑feedback self‑stabilisation; in a solid medium, lacking thermal expansion and rapid heat dissipation, energy continuously accumulates.

Key statistical property: The event rate of Path I is determined by the total number of nuclides, collision frequency, and single‑event probability. With N_total ∼10⁵⁷, even if only a tiny fraction of nuclides satisfy the reaction condition within a statistical time window, their absolute number is still large enough to produce macroscopic effects. These nuclides do not require “synchronisation” – they reach the condition independently in their local environments, as a natural outcome of statistical distributions.

Path II (forced chain reconnection): When the energy released by Path I causes the local centre of the star to cross the threshold of the total compressive binding energy (E_抗压), the connecting edges are sheared in bulk and chain reconnection initiates. The trigger involves only a small fraction of nuclides in the high‑energy core region; the released shockwave is drastically amplified through chain reactions.

Total compressive binding energy (E_抗压): The structural threshold that a topological knot can withstand against external compression, determined by the strength of the woven configuration; it does not presuppose any internal decomposition structure. This resistance exists for all types of nuclides, charged or neutral.

Path III (topological dissolution): When the algebraic sum of the topological charges of two nuclides is exactly zero, defect‑complementary engagement does not form a new stable configuration; instead, the whole structure dissolves completely because the global stress cancels, leaving only pure radiation and converting 100% of the mass into energy. This channel is extremely improbable under natural conditions but exists in principle.

3.4 Core Principles

Path I energy release is statistical – a tiny fraction of nuclides independently reach local reaction conditions, but the huge total particle number makes their absolute number sufficient to drive the star’s centre across the Path II threshold.
Path II triggering is local – a small fraction of nuclides in the high‑energy core participate in chain reconnection, releasing a shockwave.
The energy released by Path II is far smaller than the total internal energy of the star and cannot change its macroscopic thermodynamic state.
4. The “Stress‑Accumulation → Trigger → Release” Mechanism for Pulsar Emission

4.1 Complete Energy Cycle

Phase 1: Path I continuously operates, accumulating stress.

Path I runs steadily in the solid network. Statistically, a tiny fraction of nuclides independently reach local reaction conditions, releasing tiny amounts of heat and stress. Because the total particle number is enormous, the overall effect makes the stress in the central region approach the E_抗压 threshold.

Phase 2: Local centre crosses the threshold → Path II triggers.

When the accumulated stress in the core reaches E_抗压, Path II triggers – connecting edges are sheared in bulk and chain reconnection starts. Only a small fraction of nuclides in the high‑energy core region need to reach the critical condition. Path II releases a shockwave on millisecond timescales.

Phase 3: Shockwave propagation → pulse.

The shockwave propagates through the solid network to the entire spherical surface. In an oblate spheroid, different directions have different path lengths, so the arrival times at different surface points differ slightly. When the shockwave reaches the outer layer, the wavefront compresses the surface nuclides; if the energy exceeds the instantaneous tolerance of the surface layer, a “squash‑head” spallation occurs, ejecting charged fragments.

Phase 4: Narrow pulse = short shockwave duration + line‑of‑sight window.

The shockwave front is extremely narrow, and its passage through a given location lasts only milliseconds. The observer is very far away and can receive signals only from a very small patch along the line of sight. The narrowness of the pulse comes from the intrinsic short duration of the shockwave and the geometric selection of the line‑of‑sight window – it does not depend on rapid rotation or magnetic axis tilt.

Phase 5: Path II release finished → returns to Path I.

The energy released by the Path II shockwave is much smaller than the star’s total internal energy and does not change the macroscopic thermodynamic state. The star returns to Path I and restarts stress accumulation, waiting for the next local centre to cross the threshold.

Phase 6: Cycle repeats.

Stress accumulation → local centre crosses E_抗压 → Path II triggers → shockwave → pulse → return to Path I → re‑accumulation. A stable “stress‑accumulation → trigger → release” cycle is established.

4.2 Origin and Stability of the Period

Period = time required for stress to accumulate to the trigger threshold.

The accumulation rate is set by the macroscopic statistical event rate of Path I. Because the total particle number is huge and the macroscopic state after each pulse is virtually unchanged, the accumulation rate is highly stable.

Physical basis of period stability: from particle statistics to femtosecond precision

Given:

Neutron‑star particle pool: N_total ∼ 10⁵⁷
Single‑collision defect‑matching probability: p_match (intrinsic geometric probability of Path I)
Particle collision frequency: f_coll
Pulse period: P
Why the reaction rate inside a neutron star far exceeds that in the solar core:

The Path I effective probability in the solar core is ∼10⁻²⁹, based on the calculation in §3.1. The conditions inside a neutron star differ fundamentally:

Extremely high density (∼10¹⁷ kg/m³, about 12 orders of magnitude higher than the solar core): nuclide spacing shrinks dramatically, raising f_coll from ∼10⁶–10¹¹ s⁻¹ in the solar core to ∼10¹⁷–10²² s⁻¹ or even higher.
Strong anisotropic stress in the solid medium: continuous gravitational compression imposes huge anisotropic stresses on the connecting edges of the topological network. Nuclides in stress‑concentrated regions have their surface defect exposure greatly enhanced compared with those in fluid random collisions – this effectively raises the matching probability by increasing the available exposed defect area and interaction time.
Thermal enhancement of defect exposure: the local temperature rise caused by Path I’s heat release further promotes defect activation.
Combining these factors, the effective event rate (p_match × f_coll) of Path I inside a neutron star is about 15–25 orders of magnitude higher than in the solar core.

Quantitative derivation:

Let p_eff be the effective per‑particle per‑second probability of Path I inside the neutron star.

Within a single pulse period P, the total number of Path I events in the whole star is:

N_path1 = N_total × p_eff × P

According to Poisson statistics, the relative fluctuation of independent events is:

δN_path1 / N_path1 = 1 / √(N_path1)

Accuracy requirement and fulfilment:

For a millisecond pulsar (P ∼ 1 ms), the timing precision requires the relative period fluctuation ≤ 10⁻¹⁵.

To meet this, it is sufficient that:

1/√(N_path1) ≤ 10⁻¹⁵ → N_path1 ≥ 10³⁰

Substituting N_total ∼ 10⁵⁷, we require:

p_eff × P ≥ 10⁻²⁷

That is, if each particle undergoes Path I at least 10⁻²⁷ times per period, the period stability naturally reaches below femtosecond level (for a 1‑ms pulsar, absolute fluctuation < 10⁻¹⁸ s).

Physical realisation: Inside a neutron star, each particle collides about 10¹⁷–10²² times per second. Multiplying by the matching probability (conservatively taken as 10⁻²⁹), the per‑second effective event rate is about 10⁻¹²–10⁻⁷ per particle. For P = 1 ms, each particle has about 10⁻¹⁵–10⁻¹⁰ effective events per period, yielding a total of about 10⁴²–10⁴⁷ events for the whole star.

This number far exceeds the threshold of 10³⁰. The relative fluctuation is about 10⁻²¹–10⁻²³, and the absolute fluctuation about 10⁻²⁴–10⁻²⁶ s, well below femtosecond (10⁻¹⁵ s).

Conclusion: As long as the neutron‑star particle pool is large enough (10⁵⁷) and the product of collision frequency and matching probability yields more than 10³⁰ events per period, the period stability naturally reaches and surpasses the femtosecond precision required by millisecond pulsar observations. In this framework, the ultra‑high density, strong stress fields, and continuous compression provide an event number far beyond this threshold; femtosecond stability is an inevitable consequence of the law of large numbers.

4.3 Origin of Directionality and Pulse Profiles

Directionality: The shockwave arrives at the whole surface, and every part of the surface ejects fragments. The observer sees only the small patch along the line of sight. Directionality is a natural consequence of viewing geometry, requiring no magnetic inclination.

Profile diversity: The shockwave travels through the oblate spheroid, with slightly different arrival times at different surface locations. As the line‑of‑sight window sweeps across the surface, signals from different positions are superposed in time – forming single‑, double‑, or multi‑peaked profiles.

Profile stability: Each trigger occurs under the same conditions (same central E_抗压 threshold), so the shockwave generation, propagation path, and surface fragmentation pattern are the same each time → stable profile.

Nulling and intermittency: If statistical fluctuations cause a deviation in the accumulation during a given cycle, the trigger window might be missed and the next pulse occurs only in the following cycle.

4.4 Unification of Glitches, Magnetars, and the Death Line

Glitches: Abnormal concentration of stress in a certain core region triggers a larger‑scale Path II event. More connecting edges are sheared, the structure reorganises locally, the stress accumulation rate or the trigger threshold changes abruptly, causing a period jump. This is the same mechanism as ordinary pulses, but on a larger scale.

Magnetars: A larger region of the core reaches the Path II condition, producing a more energetic shockwave that radiates in X‑rays and gamma rays. Magnetars, glitches, and ordinary pulses are all the same mechanism at different scales.

Death line: No sharp boundary exists. As mass is continuously lost, the macroscopic parameters evolve, the accumulation time gradually lengthens, the shockwave intensity decreases, intermittency increases, and eventually Path II stops triggering altogether. After that, Path I continues at a very low rate, producing faint thermal radiation, with the temperature approaching but never reaching absolute zero.

